posts.raw_content:
Wokeness has infested the agency, and more importantly, they've been ripping off the American people, and it's easy to see.

We have sent 6 rovers to mars. We didn't need to send 6. We only needed to send 1. We always get the excuse of weight savings, but how much was the weight costs in total to send 6. Certainly more than sending a single robust rover built to last. 

One of the biggest failure points was Curiosity's wheels. They're practically aluminum foil. If you've seen pictures of them, they have holes all in them. How much difference would it have made to make them 2, 3, 10 times as thick? Or use a better material? Not much in the grand scheme of things. It could have done soo much more. But we don't even need to think big rovers, why not hundreds or thousands of micro rovers? 

If we're going to send something that isn't built to last long, then might as well get more coverage out of it. Meanwhile the sum total of distance traveled by Curiosity was a paltry 22 miles. A thousand micro rovers could have covered more ground in a single day. The ideology that has infected NASA is quite literally retarded, and extremely shortsighted. Of course you also need to have room to house tools, but how many samples did Curiosity take? 42 rock samples. 100 micro rovers could have taken twice that in a single day. Even if we lost half of them on deployment, we'd still be doing better than Curiosity did, for a fraction of the cost.

I think an initiative should be made that if anything sent out to planets by NASA isn't designed to last 100 years minimum, it doesn't get sent, unless it's something like a larger encompassing swarm of micro devices. The requirement can be that simple. Most of what NASA does isn't about space exploration, it's about keeping the money flowing in continuously. That's why they build stuff that isn't as robust or as useful as it could be. 

There are also other things we could tighten the funding on. For example, the GPS system. Americans pay millions of dollars every day to operate it, but the world gets it for free. That should end. Every nation using it should have to pay a yearly fee to get access to it, and it doesn't even need to be a for profit venture, but it could at least be to cover the operating costs. That seems fair to me. 

Same with NASA's deep space communications network. Other nations get access to it for free, we pay for it all. NASA has basically been operating as its own version of USAID for foreign countries. NASA even participates in many other things terrestrially, such as when landslide disasters happen in foreign countries, NASA actually spends our money and uses NASA resources to aid them in analyzing the situation. That may sound noble, but it's nothing more than slavery of the American taxpayer in the end. 

America has done soo much for the world, while being spit at. Maybe because it's free some people in government think it keeps countries from bothering to develop their own, giving "American dominance" in such areas, but it means jack shit if countries just become welfare recipients on the taxpayers dime, especially since all these countries give nothing back in return anyways. 

So what good is that dominance worth? It's like saying the slaves were the ones really in charge because the slave masters needed them. And that's what all these bad policies have turned Americans into: Slaves to the rest of the world. It was supposed to be a 2 way street, but it never worked out like that. Americans give, foreigners take, but foreigners never give, and under these policies, there's no mechanism built in that forces foreigner to give back. It all needs to end, because it's not doing any good for America.
